System Interaction Flow Description

This system consists of two core phases: "Password Registration" and "Password Verification." The following are the detailed trigger mechanisms for each interactive element in the interface:

I. Password Registration Phase (index.html)

"▶ Start" (Start Timer) Button

User Action: Click this button.

System Response:

Triggers a high-precision timer in the background; the time label on the right begins scrolling in real time (accurate to milliseconds).

Unlocks the previously grayed-out, disabled emoji/numeric keyboard below, allowing the user to start clicking.

The button itself becomes grayed out and unavailable to prevent repeated clicks.

Tab Switching ("Emoji Password" / "Numeric PIN")

User Action: Clicks to switch between emoji password and numeric password modes.

System Response:

Instantly clears the currently entered password slots.

Resets the timer to zero and relocks the keyboard, requiring the user to click "Start" again to enter passwords.

Switch the keyboard type displayed below (20-grid emoji or 3x4 numeric keypad).

"🔀 Randomize keyboard layout..." checkbox

User action: Check or uncheck the box.

System response:

Checked: Immediately and completely randomizes the current keyboard layout. Afterward, each time the user clicks "Clear" to clear the password or switches tabs, the system automatically generates a completely new random layout to prevent onlookers from recording the key positions.

Unchecked: Restores the standard fixed layout (emojis in default order, numbers arranged according to the dial pad 1-9, 0).

Virtual keyboard keys (Enter password)

User action: Click on a specific emoji or number.

System response:

Enter the selected character into the password slot above.

Shoulder Surfing Protection: Characters displayed in plaintext on the screen for 0.5 seconds are automatically converted to a mask (emojis become green "✓", numbers become black dots "•").

When 4 characters are entered, the system automatically stops the timer, locks the keyboard, and activates the "Submit" button at the bottom.

"Clear" Button

User Action: Click the Clear button.

System Response: Clears all password slots, resets the timer to zero (if on the registration page), locks the keyboard (requires clicking Start again), and determines whether to shuffle the keyboard based on the checkbox status.

"Submit" Button

User Action: Click after entering 4 characters of password.

System Response:

The frontend packages the plaintext password, group, and high-precision selection time (selection_time) and sends it to the backend API (/api/save_password).

A success message pops up, displaying the user's unique "Test ID (Record ID)" generated by the database, along with the time taken for this input.

After closing the pop-up, the interface is automatically cleared, preparing for the next input.

II. Password Verification Stage (verify.html) Most of the basic interactions on the verification page (such as the masking mechanism and random keyboard switching) are the same as on the registration page, but there are the following unique interaction logics:

"Enter your Study ID" text box

User action: Enter the numeric ID assigned by the system pop-up during registration (e.g., 1, 2, 3...).

System response: This is the "identity index." When the user clicks "verify," the system uses this ID to search for the corresponding original password record in the database.

"Verify" button

User action: Enter the ID and a full 4-digit verification password, then click the button.

System response (requesting backend comparison):

Password correct: A success message containing "✅" pops up, displaying the number of verification attempts. The page refreshes automatically after clicking "confirm."

Incorrect password (401 status): A pop-up error message containing "❌" appears ("Incorrect password, please try again.").

Error penalty and retry mechanism: The system automatically increments the "currentAttempts" count in the backend by 1 and displays "Attempt: X" in bright red font above the password field. Simultaneously, the password field is cleared, prompting the user to retry until the correct password is entered.

"📊 Export All Study Data (CSV)" button

User action: Click this button.

System response: Triggers the browser's download mechanism, accessing the backend's /api/export_data interface. The backend will convert all data in the database (including time spent, plaintext password, number of attempts, etc.) into a .csv table file, named with the current timestamp (e.g., study_data_export_20260319_...csv), and automatically download it to the user's computer.
